<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Heartjoys asked:What were your reasons for homeschooling? Major problems with the public/private systems or something minor?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
With gradeschool, my kids had (now) a great little school that was public, very close to home and still said prayers at meetings, which is unusual for public schools.  I also had a wonderful relationship with most of the teachers and faculty members at this little school.  <br>
When my eldest went to middle school it all changed.  They asked for parental involvement, but they really do not want it.  It was a much much larger school, the children were packed tighter than sardines in the classroom.  I think I told you when we met what all went on?  The teachers basically stayed out of the hallways between classes and even after school, so the kids were free to do whatever they pleased.  And what they pleased wasn't usually very nice, to put it mildly. The eighth graders bullied the younger students, I watched it happen.  There were parents that were attacked by the kids at this school.  Unbelievable! <br>
<br>
Yes there was major trouble at the school, we battled it out for 2 years at this middle school.  Both academics and behavior were problems there, and no one had the time or energy to really work things out.  When a principal tells you you ought to spank your children, at age 13?  I think it's a little beyond reasonable. The academics I won't go into, I will say my daughter was in advanced classes and there hadn't been any problems until this school.  The straw that broke the camel's back was when there was a fight at the school, my daughter had been jumped in the stairwell.  They didn't bother calling me and informing me.  One student's mom protested the punishment of suspension, that's when I was  called and told I might have to appear in court with Sarah, if the situation wasn't settled.  That's when I found out about the whole situation.  It wasn't right, and I know any of the teachers there would have been hopping mad if it had been their child involved?  Anyway, A-Becka gave us a way out of the situation, plus helped heal the previous 2 years of stress.<br>
<br>
For us, putting Sarah in a private Christian school was the best move available.  It took her a year to really get comfortable there and start trusting people.  She was waiting for the rug to be pulled out from under her again, I think.  She graduates this year, with friends and an easy going manner she had lost during those few years at the middle school. The other two I didn't even bother with sending to this middle school. It is not worth the energy nor the pain that was inflicted on my first to even attempt it.  From my understanding it's not gotten any better there.<br>
Pray about it, and see what doors God opens for you, it may be the public grade school is fine?  Be involved, talk to your son's teachers.  There are still some good ones out there.  I'll be praying for you too.<br>
<br>
God bless,<br>
Von<br>
